{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_kesil_ver01/data/sn89053729/00393344581/1913111102/0775.xml":{"full_text":"2\nsum smith\nINCONTROL\nHI MAGON\nMiller Aidermen, Though in Ma\njority, Agree to New Mayor\u2019s\nOfficial Slate.\nMACON, Nov. 11.\u2014When Bridge-\nSmith becomes Mayor of Ma on to\nmorrow be will give the most impor\nant committee chairmanship within\n:4s appointing power to the leader\n*.he faction opposed to him In Council\nby making Joseph B Riley chairman\nof the Finance Committee. As Mi\nRiiej led the Aldermanic ticket, re\nelving e\\en more votes than the\nAi tyor. e Ai l also be appointed May\nor Pro i'em, in pursuance of custom\nOther important committee chair\nmanships to be named by Mr. Smith\n\u2022re R. C. Hazlehurst, of police; F.\njunr e department; D. G Lee.\ns t i*e ts.\nCtii 1./* r is a change in the\nadministration to-rnoFrovx. city em\nployees nd other officials w ill not be\nnolested for another month, as their\n\u2022erm\u00ab do not expire until December 17\nAction of the Aldermen-elect who\nvei e named on an anti-administra\n.oii platform ir agreeing to retain in\nojce nine the principal, officials of\npresen: administration has sub\ne. ted them to much criticism from\niei? supporters. Incidental\u2019!.', it has\naused great disappointment among\nhose who were applicants sot office\nndei t. citj g<*' einm<nl\nAgree to Mayor's Ticket.\nL.i i week the ten Aldermen who\n.ere ch i.-en on the Miller ticket ta<\n.tly agreed upon men for practically\nevery one of the city offices, and it\nwas understood that another caucus\nsnould be held last night tn decide\ndefinitely on the appointments. How\never, at a conference with Mayor\n\u2022\u25a0ect Smith and the two Aldermen who\nwore elected on his ticket, when the\nof a City Clerk to succeed\nMr. Smith was the only matter ached\nuled for action, nine of Mr Smith s\nsupporters had been kept in office and\nihe Miller caucus \".slate\u2019\u2019 had been\n.ist to the w inds. A Mermen-elect\nRiley. Pittman, Stevens mid Taylor\nvoted with Mr. Smith and his two Al\ndermen, Messrs. Hazlehurst and Jones\nThis is taken to indicate that the\n>1 filer x ermei they ha\\ beat\n.nown until now. will not take ad\nantage of their light to arrogate to\nhemselves the appointment of all of\nthe firemen and policemen, but will\nontinue to allow tile power to vest in\nhe Mayor, subject to ratification b\\\nhe whole Council.\nSlate of New Officials.\nSome of the new administrations\n\u2022fficlals w ill be Walter Defore, City!\n\\ttorney; Davis S. Jones, City Clerk;\nWillard Gates. Marshal; Harrison i\nJonson. Treasurer; J. J. Gaillard, En\ngineer; C. H. Humphries. Electrician;\nW. Hubbard, Sexton; G. F. Alex\nander. Plumbing Inspector; T. J\nCochran. City Recorder; F. Joe Bish-,\nup, Building Inspector; Seymour Al.\nBrown. License Inspector. George W. I\nOxley, Street Suj\u00bberlntondent: 1..\nMiller. Fire Chief.\nThe nominees for Chief of Police,\nv\u2019lty Physician and Chief Sanitary In- 1\ntpector have not been agreed upon.\nAtco Stands for good,\npure, medium priced Cof\nfee-made in Atlanta.\n\nr\u2019Jz\u2019Zj\nAddress\nV PAf A LIT TLE 7\nAT A TIME 3 J\nW L AT THE S\n?>FAIR q\n5 Beautiful j\nNew\n?Im Fall I\nn/4 Suits 1\n\\|J $12.50\nW $35.00 I\nand\nCoats at $lO 7\nto $35.00\nA For Ladies and Misses 1\ni/ Pay For These Stylish 4\nS Garments While Yon\nWear Them 2\nDignified, helpful credit\nnot a mere thirty days* I\n|m charge account\u2014but time to Jf\nL pay suiting your tonven\nCome in to-morrow ano X\n\u2022X ee how well every high jl\nW class autumn mode Is rep\nA resented at LOWER prices.\nF Visit our big millinery de>\npartment and open a w\nJ CHARGE ACCOUNT. T\n>THE FAIR\nS 93 WHITEHALL\nFREE COUPON\nIn HEARST\u2019S SI MMY AMERICAN and VE\nLA XT A<l E< )R( iI AX 1 it Christmas <iif t> Dis\ntribution.\nGOOD FOR 5 VOTES\nFor\nAddress\nI list\nEill in your favorite\u2019s name, and send to\nOffer Department, ami votes will be credited\nin favor of candidate.\nXot ijood after Xovember 20.\nA Government Central\nBank Is a Good Dem\nocratic Ideal\nMr. Jacob H. Schiff has conferred a distinct service by his\nspeech in regard to currency legislation. One does not have to\nagree with him in every point to appreciate the value and the\nilluminating character of his utterances. Mr. Schiff's speech\ncan hardly be considered alarmist. The points that he makes are:\nFirst. That the currency legislation before Congress ought\nto be completed as speedily as may be, since delay mean usneer\ntainty, and uncertainty is always a disturbing influence in the\nbusiness world.\nSecond. That, despite the desirability of a prompt conclusion\nof the currency question, nevertheless sufficient time should be\ntaken to make the new currency measure absolutely sound and\neffective.\nThird. That too protracted deliberation over the currency\nmeasure, and too prolonged uncertainty as to what business con\nditions would be as a result of the currency measure, would prob\nably bring about a business stagnation and a lack of confidence\nwhich would result in business depression sufficiently aggravated\nto be pronounced a panic.\nFourth. That the present administration measure is a modi\nfication of the Aldrich bill. and. to a large extent, the product\nof the monetary commission, of vfhicn Senator Aldrich was the\nhead, and that, therefore, he, Mr. Schiff, and other representa\ntives of the great Wall street interests could find less danger in\nthe prompt passage of the administration bill than in delay and\nthe possible failure to pass it.\nIf the above is a correct analysis of Mr. Schiff 's speech, how\ncan anyone criticise his remarks, even if they do not wholly\nagree with his conclusions?\nUndoubtedly and indisputably, the prompt passage of a cor\nrect currency bill is desirable and the prompt passage of a cor\nrect tariff measure. The continual and protracted disturbance\nof business does cause business depression, and sufficient business\ndullness and financial depression have already been caused by the\ndidactic doctrines and the infallible theories of the present peda\ngogic administration.\nObviously, however, enough time must be given to discus,\nsion and deliberation over this currency measure to prevent a se\nrious mistake being made, similar to the mistake made in the\ntariff act.\nThe country should not. be rushed into a measure which\nis undemocratic in principle and which will not inure to the\nbenefit of the people, as we were rushed into a measure of tariff\nreduction which opened our markets to the products of foreign\ncountries without opening foreign markets to the products of our\ncountry.\nCertainly, for instance, we do not wish to see the country\nhurried into the adoption of a merely modified Aldrich measure.\nThe people of this country expressed with sufficient emphasis\ntheir doubt and disapproval of the Aldrich provisions and the\nAldrich intentions.\nNo matter how honest the purposes of the present builders\not the administration bill it is doubtful if a merely reconstructed\nAldrich bill will sufficiently satisfy the requirements of the situa\ntion or the demands of the progressive elements of the com\ninunity.\nIf Mr. Schiff is right, and apparently is right, in stating that\nthe administration bill is merely an outgrowth of the Aldrich\nrecommendations, would it not be better for this presumptively\nprogressive administration to start from another foundation and\nnot merely remodel their structure, but construct a new financial\nmeasure from the ground up?\nWould it not be better to proceed along the lines of the\nproposal of Mr. Vanderlip. Would it not be better to adopt the\njudiciously radical declaration of the Independence Party plat\nform adopted at Chicago in ISOB and reading\n'The Independence Party declares that the right to issue\nmoney is inherent in the government AND IT FAVORS THE ES\nTABLISHMENT OF A CENTRAL GOVERNMENT BANK\nthrough which the money so issued shall be put into general cir\nculation.\u201d\nThe soundest and most advanced progressive thought of this\ncountry has long been in favor of a central, government con\ntrolled bank. The established principle and practice of the great\nRepublic of France is expressed in the form of the Bank of\nFrance, a central, government controlled bank.\nThe most thorough and thoughtful, and yet the most ad\nvanced opinion in Germany finds expression in the Reichsbank\nof Berlin, a central, government controlled bank.\nThe plan is practical, because it is in successful operation in\nother great and up-to-date nations.\nIt is democratic and progressive and in accordance with our\nAmerican ideas and institutions.\nA democratic and progressive administration should favor\nthe idea of a central, government controlled bank, and a prac\ntical business administration of this government should adopt\nthis plan, especially when the plan has the support not only of\nthe people at large, who will be benefited by it, but of such\ngreat bankers as Mr. Vanderlip, who recognize the practicability\nof this plan and its essential soundness and value.\nMr. Schiff\u2019 is right when he states that unnecessary delay\nis dangerous, but he is wrong, so far as the popular interest and\ninclination are concerned, when he advocates the adoption of\nof the truly democratic proposition of a central, government\nof the modified Aldrich administration measure,\nMr. Schiff and Mr. Vanderlip should unite in their support\ncontrolled bank, conducted not by any clique in the interest of\nany class, but by the government in the interest of all classes in\nall sections of the country.\nWILLIAM RANDOLPH HEARST\ni n r, a t laa i a iir;uK<tiAA AMJ LEVY'S.\nPOLITICAL TINGE\nTO WINEGOFF\nBANOUET\nThree Prospective Mayoralty Can\ndidates, Guests of Harrell.\nMake Significant Remarks.\nNo one expected any political\nspeeches at the banquet and jollifi\n-1 a lion given at the Hotel Wlnecoff\nb\\ Manager Frank Harrell to his\nfriend* Munday night. No real po-\nIftichl -pewhis were heard, but the\nlittle three-minute talks inatlo by\nthree rn\u00ab*n who have been mentioned\nmayoralty candidates in the next\nity election meant more than good\nnatured jesting.\nMayor Woodward, Walter P. An\ndrews and Forrest Adair were pres- J\nent. In a short speech Mayor Wood- I\nward announced that he would be in I\nt. e thickest of the going at the next I\nelection.\nIntroduc'd by Toastmaster .1 Y\nSmith, f\u2019o\u2019onel Andrews, appointed\nI riited States Commissioner to the\nMediterranean nations lor the Pana\nma Pacific Exposition, said:\n\"For years I have supported the\nat ministration of Jim Woodward, and\nI have been one of his most ardent\nadmirers. Much, indeed, he has done j\nfor Atlanta. I am going away on a I\nmission of importance tor my coun\ntry. and when I return I hope to r\nreive the well wishes of my fellow\npeople. I introduce to you Forrest\nAdair, the next Mayor of Atlanta.\"\nMr. Adair spoke without referring\nto the race.\nLater in the evening Colonel An\ndrew- aid that under certain civic\nonditi' n.s he would run for Mayor. I\nbut ould not announce this as a I\n-urety until next summer, when he j\nrctiP'ns from Europe.\nThe entertainment was a great s\u2019l\n\u2022ess and brought out some of the\nading tlzens Vtiant i. The din\nner could not have been improved\nupon. Interesting talks were mat\nby Colonel Robert Lowry. Colom.-i\nFrederh J. I\u2019.xon and Charles L.\nLight.\nIndoor Winter Baseball\nHearst's Sunday American I\nand The Atlanta Georgian 5) Home Diamond\nEnables You to Play at Home\nWINTER EVENINGS, with the storm raging outside, will find you looking for amusement as you\nsit in a vomfoitable chair before a cozy fire. \u201cHome Diamond\u201d will provide entertainment for\nyou, whethei you play it alone or with a partner. Even the onlookers will share the merriment\nand excitement. Here is an indoor game full of the memories of thrilling finishes and tense situations of\nthe past seasons ball games, duplicated play for play with almost uncanny fidelity. \u201cTw\u2019o down and the\njases full, tied in the ninth and similar crises occur in a big percentage of the games. Famous plays\nmay also be duplicated and new ideas tried out.\n\nTl n\nli\nMl fc? [j\nVo\n\na ways active no quiet moments\nNEVER OUT OF SIGHT EVERY MOVE A PLAY\nCall to-day at the offices. If you can't call, ascertain from your postmaster the Dostave nn a\nyour home town and add it to your remittance of fifty cents and one heading of The American or Georgian 6 ame P P ost rom Atlanta to\nMEARSTS\nDAILY .SUNDAY*\nCIRCULATION DEPT. ATLANTA GA\n20 EAST ALABAMA ST.\nTO DAY\u2019S MARKET\nOPENINGS.\nNEW ORLEANS COTTON.\ni i i IFlrstl Prev\nlOpnn High Low ICall 1 Clog*\ni j~~ .7'13122-24\n1\" 13.-5 13.26 13.25 13.26'13.30-31\nJun. 13.27 13.23 13.27 13.26 13.32-33\nFeb. 13.44-46\nM'-h 13.36 13.36 13.35 13.35 13.40-41\nApri113.42-44\nMay 13.41 13.41;13.41 13.41'13.46-47\nJune 13.46-43\n18.43-51\n\nNEW YORK COTTON.\ni J t First| Tr\u00ab-\n>Open|High;Low I Cali.l Cloa*\nNov. 1 12.98-01\n\u20193 -8 12.32 13.28 13.32 13.36-37\nlan. 13.0413.U7 13.03 13.06 13.12-14\ni eb:113.10-12\nMeh. 13'. 13113.14 13.12 13.14 13.20-21\nAprill3.l7-19\nMay 13.13113.16 13.13 13.14 13.20-21\nJune 13.15-19\nJul' 13.06 13.08 13.06|13.08 13.13-14\n.12.95-97\nLIVERPOOL COTTON MARKET.\nFutures opened quiet.\nOoeninr;\nRange 2p. m. Clowe.\nXo'\nNov.-Dec. .7.08 -7.06 7.04 7.00%\nDec.-Jan. .7.07 -7.06 6.99%\nJan.-Feb. .7.06 -7 04% 7.03% 6.99%\nFeb.-Men. .7.06%-7.05% 7.00\nAl.-h -April .7 07 -7.05% 7.04% 7.00%\nMa ,7.0\u00ab 7.01\n7 05% 7.ol\u2019\u25a0\u25a0\nI June-July .7.04%-7.05% 7.00\nI July-Aug. .7.05 -7.03 7.01% 6.98%\nI Aug.-Sept. .6.85 -6.86 6.8:: 680\nSep*.-Oci 6.57 6.54\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET.\nStock quotations to 10 a. m.:\n10 Prev.\nSTOCKS High Low A.M. Close.\nAma). <\u2019opper. 68 7 s \u00abB*,s 68 T 8 68%\nAmerican Can 17 16 7 s 27 26\nAm Cot. Oil. 36% .26% 36% 36%\nAtchison 91 91 91\nar.d O. 55% 55% 55% 55%\njjnterboro 13 18 13 13%\ndo. pref. 57 57 57 57%\nMo. Pacific.. 26% 26 y 26%\nN and. W 103 u 1.03% 103%\nPennsylvania. 107% 107% 107% 107%\nReading 158 158% 158% 158\nSo. Pacific...\nt. Pau199,1 91 \u25a0'n 9\u00ab14\nI\u2019nion Pacific. 118% 148% 148% 147%\nI\u2019. S. Steel... 54% 54% 54% 54%\nWilson Pardons Man\nWho Fled U. S. in \u201993\ni WASHINGTON, Nov. 11.\u2014William\nDunbar, who was convicted in 1893\nin Oregon of smuggling opium and\nwho fled to China to escape impris-\nt.nmeni 20 years ago. was pardoned\nto-day by President Wilson.\nDunbar has grown rich in China.\nGEORGIA WOMEN\nBEGIN NIISSIDN\nCONVENTION\nj\nTwo Thousand Delegates Assem-I\nble at Tabernacle\u2014Meeting to\nLast Through Friday.\ni\nI Nearly 2,000 women, half of them\ni j from out-of-town, assembled in the\n1 Baptist Tabernacle at 10 o\u2019clock Tues\nday morning at the twenty-fifth an\nnual session of the Women\u2019s Mission-\nary Union# South. The program was I\ndesigned to last throughout the day. 1\nand Wednesday the thirty-first annual\nmeeting of the Georgia Women\u2019s Bap-\nI tist Missionary Union will begin.\nMrs. W. J. Neel, of Cartersville\nPresident of the Executive Board of\nthe Georgia. Union, presided at the\nmorning session, and will also occupy\nI the chair at the afternoon meeting,\nj Mrs. Sam D. Jones, of Atlanta, will\nofficiate at the evening session.\nAt the morning session, the princi\npal address was delivered by Mrs. J.\nU. Lanier, of West Point, on \u201cA His\ntory of the Women's Missionary*\ni Union, Auxiliary to the Southern Bap\ntist Convention.\u2019\u2019\nMrs. A. J. Orme\u2019s topic was Pio-\nneers in the Women\u2019s Baptist\nsionary Union of Georgia,\u201d and at the\nend of her talk 30 of the oldest mem\nbers of the union, in point of active\nservice, were called to the rostrum J\n**ach being applauded as her name\nwas called, and benig presented with\na white rose.\n\u201dOur National 2Nseed\u201d was the sub\nject of Miss Kathleen Mallory, of\nBaltimore, who. \"with Miss F. E. S.\nI Heck, of Raleigh, N. is a guest\nof Mrs, Sam D. Jones, of Atlanta.\n\u2014j\nSquare Deal Coffee is\neverything its name im\nplies. Roasted daily and\nblended in Atlanta.\nSPECIAL PRICE C/V\nWith One Heading of Either Hearst\u2019s American or The Atlanta Georgian If\nPostage Extra. Weight 30 Ounces. V\nOnly a limited number of the -e games have been secured and\nthey will be sold by THE HEARST\u2019S SUNDAY AMERICAN AND\nTHE ATLANTA GEORGIAN exclusively. You can\u2019t buy them else\nwhere at any price and you may not get one at all unless you call or\nsend for it immediately. This is an opportunity that may be with\ndrawn within a very few days\u2014only prompt action will prevent dis\nappointment. Call for your game TO DAY.\nSome Features of the Game\nBALLS.\nA batter may \"get on\" by drawing four\nballs. Some of the provisions in connec\ntion with a \"ball\u201d cover a \u201cwild pitch and\npassed ball runner out attempting to\nsteal second: runner safe stealing second\nor third.\nSTRIKES.\nA strike either may be called or a foul.\nIn conjunction with a strike, a runner\nmay lie enabled to steal home nr may be\nput out in the effort to steal third\nHITS.\nSingles, two-baggers, three-base hits and\nhome runs are all provided for. Just as\nin the regular game, three-base hits are\nl scarcer than two-baggers and home runs\nA are not at all common. Frequently a\nXX game is played with very little hitting,\u2019 the\nbatters going out \"one. two. three.\u201d\n[SSEIHH\nThe Kind Yon Have Always Bought has borne the signa\nture of Chas. 11. Fletcher, and has been made under hi*\npersona) supervision for over 30 years. Allow no one\nto deceive you in this. Counterfeits, Imitations and\n\u00abItist-as-good sire but Experiments, and endanger the\nhealth of Children\u2014Experience against Experiment.\nWhat is CASTORIA\nOvdoria is a harmless substitute for Castor Oil, Pare\ngoric, Drops and Soothing Syrups. It is Pleasant. It\ncontains neither Opium, Morphine nor other Narcotic\nsubstance. Its age is its guarantee. It destroys Worms\nand allays Feverishness. It cures Diarrhicr. and 'Wind.\nColic. It reli\u00ab ves Teething Troubles, cure; Constipation\nand Flatulency. It assimilates the Food, regulates the\nStomach and jlowels, giving healthy and natural sleep.\nThe Children\u2019s Panacea\u2014The Mother\u2019s Friend.\nThe Kind You Have Always Bought\njy Bears the Signature of\nIn Use For Over 30 Years.\nTHE CCNTMUR C9MMNV, Tt MURRAY STAECY, NEW YORK CITY.\n9\n\nGeorgian Want Ads\nOUTS.\nI'ut-outs are indicated, such as \u201cthird to\nfirst;\u201d \u201cfly to center;\u201d \u201cdouble play, sec\nond to first,\u201d etc. A groan or a cheer, ac\ncording to one's sympathies, often accom\npanies a double play with one out\nSCORING.\nindicators are provided to register the\nruns and hits of the visiting team and\nsimilar indicators keep the score for the\nhome team. Indicators for strikes, balls\nand outs also are provided, and also an\ninning indicator for each team. Run\nners on bases are also shown and the\nteam at bat is not overlooked. All these\ndevices are self-contained and neither\npencil nor paper is required to score the\ngame.\nDesks, Tables and Chairs\nFiling Devices and Bookcases\nOpera Chairs, Pews, School Desks\nSafes, Vaults, Steel Furniture\nStationery and Office Supplies\nLoose Leaf Devices\nDrawing and Artist\u2019s Materials\nTn if Office Outfitters\u201d\nFIELDER ALLEN CO,\nATLANTA. U. S. A.","height":"25057","width":"21147"}}
